# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: postgis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:postgis/documentation] We are always trying to improve the documentation.
[src:postgis/postgis] PostGIS is implemented as a *PostgreSQL external extension*.
[src:postgis/postgis] The PostGIS implementation is based on "light-weight" geometries and indexes optimized to reduce disk and memory footprint.
[src:postgis/postgis] Using light-weight geometries helps servers increase the amount of data migrated up from physical disk storage into RAM, improving query performance substantially.
[src:postgis/postgis] PostGIS is registered as "implements the specified standard" for "Simple Features for SQL" by the OGC.
[src:postgis/postgis] PostGIS has not been certified as compliant by the OGC.
[src:postgis/postgis] Refractions Research released the first version of PostGIS in 2001 under the GNU General Public License.
[src:postgis/postgis] After six release candidates, a stable "1.0" version followed on 19 April 2005.
[src:postgis/postgis] In 2006 the OGC registered PostGIS as "implement[ing] the specified standard" for "Simple Features for SQL".
[src:postgis/spatial-database] A **spatial database** is a general-purpose database (usually a relational database) that has been enhanced to include spatial data that represents objects defined in a geometric space, along with tools for querying and analyzing such data.
[src:postgis/spatial-database] Most spatial databases allow the representation of simple geometric objects such as points, lines and polygons.
[src:postgis/spatial-database] Some spatial databases handle more complex structures such as 3D objects, topological coverages, linear networks, and triangulated irregular networks (TINs).
[src:postgis/spatial-database] While typical databases have developed to manage various numeric and character types of data, such databases require additional functionality to process spatial data types efficiently, and developers have often added *geometry* or *feature* data types.
[src:postgis/spatial-database] The Open Geospatial Consortium (OGC) developed the *Simple Features* specification (first released in 1997) and sets standards for adding spatial functionality to database systems.
[src:postgis/spatial-database] The *SQL/MM Spatial* ISO/IEC standard is a part of the structured query language and multimedia standard extending the Simple Features.
[src:postgis/spatial-database] The core functionality added by a spatial extension to a database is one or more *spatial datatypes*, which allow for the storage of spatial data as attribute values in a table.
[src:postgis/spatial-database] Most commonly, a single spatial value would be a geometric primitive (point, line, polygon, etc.) based on the vector data model.
[src:postgis/spatial-database] The datatypes in most spatial databases are based on the OGC Simple Features specification for representing geometric primitives.
[src:postgis/spatial-database] Some spatial databases also support the storage of raster data.
[src:postgis/spatial-database] Because all geographic locations must be specified according to a spatial reference system, spatial databases must also allow for the tracking and transformation of coordinate systems.
[src:postgis/spatial-database] In many systems, when a spatial column is defined in a table, it also includes a choice of coordinate system, chosen from a list of available systems that is stored in a lookup table.
[src:postgis/spatial-database] The second major functionality extension in a spatial database is the addition of spatial capabilities to the query language (e.g., SQL); these give the spatial database the same query, analysis, and manipulation operations that are available in traditional GIS software.
[src:postgis/spatial-database] In most relational database management systems, this functionality is implemented as a set of new functions that can be used in SQL SELECT statements.
[src:postgis/spatial-database] Some databases support only simplified or modified sets of these operations, especially in cases of NoSQL systems like MongoDB and CouchDB.
[src:postgis/spatial-database] A **spatial index** is used by a spatial database to optimize spatial queries, implementing spatial access methods.
[src:postgis/spatial-database] Database systems use indices to quickly look up values by sorting data values in a linear (e.g. alphabetical) order; however, this way of indexing data is not optimal for spatial queries in two- or three-dimensional space.
[src:postgis/spatial-database] Instead, spatial databases use a *spatial* index designed specifically for multi-dimensional ordering.
[src:postgis/spatial-database] A **spatial query** is a special type of database query supported by spatial databases, including geodatabases.
[src:postgis/spatial-database] The queries differ from non-spatial SQL queries in several important ways.
[src:postgis/spatial-database] Two of the most important are that they allow for the use of geometry data types such as points, lines and polygons and that these queries consider the spatial relationship between these geometries.
[src:postgis/spatial-database] The function names for queries differ across geodatabases.
[src:postgis/spatial-reference-system] A **spatial reference system** (**SRS**) or **coordinate reference system** (**CRS**) is a framework used to precisely measure locations on, or relative to, the surface of Earth as coordinates.
[src:postgis/spatial-reference-system] It is thus the application of the abstract mathematics of coordinate systems and analytic geometry to geographic space.
[src:postgis/spatial-reference-system] A particular SRS specification (for example, "Universal Transverse Mercator WGS 84 Zone 16N") comprises a choice of Earth ellipsoid, horizontal datum, map projection (except in the geographic coordinate system), origin point, and unit of measure.
[src:postgis/spatial-reference-system] Thousands of coordinate systems have been specified for use around the world or in specific regions and for various purposes, necessitating transformations between different SRS.
[src:postgis/spatial-reference-system] Although they date to the Hellenistic period, spatial reference systems are now a crucial basis for the sciences and technologies of Geoinformatics, including cartography, geographic information systems, surveying, remote sensing, and civil engineering.
[src:postgis/spatial-reference-system] The above refers to locations directly on the surface of the earth.
[src:postgis/spatial-reference-system] Information on elevation may also be specified, via a vertical reference frame, so-called vertical CRS, or an integrated 3D CRS.
[src:postgis/spatial-reference-system] Terminology in this area is evolving in line with increasing technical sophistication in measurement.
[src:postgis/spatial-reference-system] , because they are based on the center of mass.
[src:postgis/spatial-reference-system] that models the surface of Earth (or more commonly, a large region thereof) as a plane, measuring locations from an arbitrary origin point along x and y axes more or less aligned with the cardinal directions.
[src:postgis/spatial-reference-system] to create a planar surface from the curved Earth surface.
[src:postgis/spatial-reference-system] Such SRSs are generally defined and used strategically in their target regions to minimize the distortions inherent to projections for specific use cases.
[src:postgis/spatial-reference-system] (2-D or 3-D) that is created bespoke for a small area, often a single engineering project, over which the curvature of the Earth can be safely approximated as flat without significant distortion.
[src:postgis/spatial-reference-system] These may or may not be aligned with a standard projected coordinate system.
[src:postgis/spatial-reference-system] are a type of local coordinate system used in aviation and marine vehicles.
[src:postgis/spatial-reference-system] This does not carry information about localization of a point on the surface of the earth, but elevation relative to the surface of the earth, importantly including specification of what zero elevation is.
[src:postgis/spatial-reference-system] Combines a geographic or projected coordinate system with a vertical reference frame to provide a full parametrization of locations on or near the surface of the earth relative to a chosen zero elevation level.
[src:postgis/spatial-reference-system] These standards acknowledge that standard reference systems also exist for time (e.g.
[src:postgis/spatial-reference-system] These may be combined with a spatial reference system to form a *compound coordinate system* for representing three-dimensional and/or spatio-temporal locations.
[src:postgis/spatial-reference-system] There are also internal systems for measuring location within the context of an object, such as the rows and columns of pixels in a raster image, Linear referencing measurements along linear features (e.g., highway mileposts), and systems for specifying location within moving objects such as ships.
[src:postgis/spatial-reference-system] The latter two are often classified as subcategories of engineering coordinate systems.
[src:postgis/spatial-reference-system] The goal of any spatial reference system is to create a common reference frame in which locations can be measured precisely and consistently as coordinates, which can then be shared unambiguously, so that any recipient can identify the same location that was originally intended by the originator.
[src:postgis/spatial-reference-system] A **Spatial Reference System Identifier** (**SRID**) is a unique value used to unambiguously identify projected, unprojected, and local spatial coordinate system definitions.
[src:postgis/spatial-reference-system] These coordinate systems form the heart of all GIS applications.
[src:postgis/spatial-reference-system] Virtually all major spatial vendors have created their own SRID implementation or refer to those of an authority, such as the EPSG Geodetic Parameter Dataset.
[src:postgis/spatial-reference-system] SRIDs are typically associated with a well-known text (WKT) string definition of the coordinate system (SRTEXT, above).
[src:postgis/spatial-reference-system] SRID values associated with spatial data can be used to constrain spatial operations — for instance, spatial operations cannot be performed between spatial objects with differing SRIDs in some systems, or trigger coordinate system transformations between spatial objects in others.
[src:postgis/well-known-text-representation-of-geometry] Coordinates for geometries may be 2D (*x*, *y*), 3D (*x*, *y*, *z*), 4D (*x*, *y*, *z*, *m*) with an *m* value that is part of a linear referencing system or 2D with an *m* value (*x*, *y*, *m*).
[src:postgis/well-known-text-representation-of-geometry] Three-dimensional geometries are designated by a "Z" after the geometry type and geometries with a linear referencing system have an "M" after the geometry type.
[src:postgis/well-known-text-representation-of-geometry] Empty geometries that contain no coordinates can be specified by using the symbol `EMPTY` after the type name.
[src:postgis/well-known-text-representation-of-geometry] WKT geometries are used throughout OGC specifications and are present in applications that implement these specifications.
[src:postgis/well-known-text-representation-of-geometry] For example, PostGIS contains functions that can convert geometries to and from a WKT representation, making them human readable.
[src:postgis/well-known-text-representation-of-geometry] The OGC standard definition requires a polygon to be topologically closed.
[src:postgis/well-known-text-representation-of-geometry] It also states that if the exterior linear ring of a polygon is defined in a counterclockwise direction, then it will be seen from the "top".
[src:postgis/well-known-text-representation-of-geometry] Any interior linear rings should be defined in opposite fashion compared to the exterior ring, in this case, clockwise.
[src:postgis/well-known-text-representation-of-geometry] Well-known binary (WKB) representations are typically shown in hexadecimal strings.
[src:postgis/well-known-text-representation-of-geometry] Each data type has a unique data structure, such as the number of points or linear rings, followed by coordinates in 64-bit double numbers.
[src:postgis/well-known-text-representation-of-geometry] (SRID) and up to 4 ordinate values (XYZM).
[src:postgis/well-known-text-representation-of-geometry] It also supports circular curves, following elements named (but not fully defined) within the original WKT: CircularString, CompoundCurve, CurvePolygon and CompoundSurface.
